  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mobilization for the tabling, enactment, and adoption of legal protection for tenancy labour farmers</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to influence the policies and legal framework that adequately protect against abuses and exploitation of tenant farmers in Malawi. Tenancy farming is an agricultural production system in which landowners contributes their land and often a measure of operating capital and management; while tenant farmers contribute their labour.  Tenant farmers are often migrant farmers (i.e. they come from other regions of Malawi-most commonly from the southern Region) who are generally amongst the poorest of the poor in Malawi, and are vulnerable to abuse. They become tenants only because they are unable to find alternative employment or are unable to sustain themselves as independent smallholder farmers. They are also located in rural areas where conditions are worse than in the urban centres. The absence of legislative protection for tenant farmers is exacerbating and critical to the perpetuation of abuses and exploitation in tenancy system. The tabling, enactment and adoption of the Tenancy Bill has been extremely slow so far. This project therefore seek to mobilise for the tabling, enactment of Legal framework regulating tenancy system; increase tenant farmers&apos; knowledge on their rights, obligations and ability to claim their space-(Education for confidence); and contribute towards creation of an environment that enables the coordinated, effective adoption of the Tenancy Labour Bill to prevent economic exploitation and other violations of tenants&#x2019; rights through media by 2015.</narrative>
  </description>
